  "local_port": 42426,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I block Skype on Mac?",
  "response": "To block Skype on a Mac, you can use several methods. Here are a few approaches:\n\n### 1. **Using Parental Controls:**\nNote: This method is suitable if you have administrative privileges and the specific version of macOS that still supports Parental Controls.\n\n1. **System Preferences**: Open `System Preferences` by clicking on the Apple logo in the top-left corner and selecting it.\n2. **Users & Groups**: Go to `Users & Groups`.\n3. **Parental Controls**: Click the lock icon to authenticate, then select the user account you wish to restrict.\n4. **Enable Parental Controls**: Select `Enable parental controls`.\n5. **Apps**: Under `Apps`, choose to restrict `App Store` apps or manage apps specifically where you can choose to block Skype.\n\n**Note**: Parental Controls have been replaced by Screen Time in newer macOS versions.\n\n### 2. **Using Screen Time (for macOS Catalina and later):**\n\n1. **System Preferences**: Open `System Preferences`.\n2. **Screen Time**: Select `Screen Time`. If you haven't turned it on, enable it.\n3. **App Limits**: Go to `App Limits`, click the plus (+) button to add an app, and find Skype to set limits.\n4. **Always Allowed**: Ensure Skype is unselected in `Always Allowed`.\n\n### 3. **Using Hosts File:**\n\n1. **Open Terminal**: You can do this by searching for Terminal in Spotlight (Cmd + Space).\n2. **Edit Hosts File**: Type `sudo nano /etc/hosts` and press Enter.\n3. **Add Skype Addresses**: Add lines such as `127.0.0.1 skype.com` to block the Skype domain.\n4. **Save Changes**: Press `Control + O` to save changes, then `Control + X` to exit the editor.\n5. **Flush DNS Cache**: In Terminal, type `sudo dscacheutil -flushcache` and press Enter to apply changes.\n\n### 4. **Use Firewall Rules:**\n\n1. **Open Firewall**: Go to `System Preferences` > `Security & Privacy` > `Firewall`.\n2. **Firewall Options**: Click on `Firewall Options`.\n3. **Block Incoming Connections**: Add Skype to the list and set it to block incoming connections.\n\n### 5. **Uninstall Skype (if needed):**\n\n1. **Quit Skype**: Ensure Skype is not running. Right-click the Skype icon in your dock and select `Quit`.\n2. **Move to Trash**: Open Finder, go to Applications, find Skype, and drag it to the Trash.\n3. **Remove Skype Data**: Go to `~/Library/Application Support/` and delete the Skype folder.\n\nChoose the method that best suits your needs depending on whether you want to restrict usage only or also remove access to the Skype application altogether.",
